# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chapman-jouguet-condition
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] The ***Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society*** is an academic journal on the history of science published annually by the Royal Society.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] It publishes obituaries of Fellows of the Royal Society.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] It was established in 1932 as *Obituary Notices of Fellows of the Royal Society* and obtained its current title in 1955, with volume numbering restarting at 1.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] Prior to 1932, obituaries were published in the *Proceedings of the Royal Society*.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] The memoirs are a significant historical record and most include a full bibliography of works by the subjects.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] The memoirs are often written by a scientist of the next generation, often one of the subject's own former students, or a close colleague.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] In many cases the author is also a Fellow.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] Notable biographies published in this journal include Albert Einstein, Alan Turing, Bertrand Russell, Claude Shannon, Clement Attlee, Ernst Mayr, and Erwin Schrödinger.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] Each year, around 40 to 50 memoirs of deceased Fellows of the Royal Society are collated by the Editor-in-Chief, currently Malcolm Longair, who succeeded Trevor Stuart in 2016.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] All contents are freely available to read.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] The **Chapman–Jouguet condition** holds approximately in detonation waves in high explosives.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] It states that the detonation propagates at a velocity at which the reacting gases just reach sonic velocity (in the frame of the leading shock wave) as the reaction ceases.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] David Chapman and Émile Jouguet originally (c.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] 1900) stated the condition for an infinitesimally thin detonation.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] A physical interpretation of the condition is usually based on the later modelling (c.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] 1943) by Yakov Borisovich Zel'dovich, John von Neumann, and Werner Döring (the so-called ZND detonation model).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] In more detail (in the ZND model) in the frame of the leading shock of the detonation wave, gases enter at supersonic velocity and are compressed through the shock to a high-density, subsonic flow.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] This sudden change in pressure initiates the chemical (or sometimes, as in steam explosions, physical) energy release.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] The energy release re-accelerates the flow back to the local speed of sound.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] It can be shown fairly simply, from the one-dimensional gas equations for steady flow, that the reaction must cease at the sonic ("CJ") plane, or there would be discontinuously large pressure gradients at that point.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] The sonic plane forms a so-called choke point that enables the lead shock, and reaction zone, to travel at a constant velocity, undisturbed by the expansion of gases in the rarefaction region beyond the CJ plane.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] This simple one-dimensional model is quite successful in explaining detonations.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] However, observations of the structure of real chemical detonations show a complex three-dimensional structure, with parts of the wave traveling faster than average, and others slower.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] Indeed, such waves are quenched as their structure is destroyed.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] The Wood–Kirkwood detonation theory can correct for some of these limitations.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] Here the subscript 1 and 2 identifies flow properties (pressure p , density $\rho$ ) upstream and downstream of the wave and m is the constant mass flux and q is the heat released in the wave.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] where M is the Mach number and c is the speed of sound, in other words, downstream flow is sonic with respect to the Chapman-Jouguet wave.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/chapman-jouguet-condition] The upper sign applies for the **Upper Chapman-Jouguet** point (detonation) and the lower sign applies for the **Lower Chapman-Jouguet** point (deflagration).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] Chapman was born in Wells, Norfolk but moved with his family to Manchester and attended Manchester Grammar School.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] He then went to Christ Church, Oxford, obtaining degrees in chemistry (1893, 1st class) and physics (1894, 2nd class).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] Campman was by reputation something of a scientific recluse, difficult to dislodge from his laboratory, although he did play a full part in University and College affairs.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] Away from his teaching and research, he was reserved and somewhat eccentric, but enjoyed golf, cycling and walking.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] He married one of his research students, Muriel Holmes (a member of the university's Society of Oxford Home-Students) in 1918 and together they had a daughter, Ruth.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] He died from cancer at his home in Oxford in 1958.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] Chapman was a science master at Giggleswick School for a time before becoming a member of staff at the University of Manchester.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] In 1907, Jesus College, Oxford appointed him as fellow and tutor in charge of its new teaching and research laboratory.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] Chapman ran this until his retirement in 1944; the laboratory, the last college-run laboratory in the university, closed in 1947.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] Chapman was also vice-principal of the college (1926–44).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] Although Chapman took a keen interest in his students, research was his main priority.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] Chapman had a particular interest in the photochemical reaction of hydrogen and chlorine, establishing that minute traces of impurities caused unexpected consequences.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] He suggested the steady state hypothesis in 1913.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/david-chapman-scientist] He discovered that the interruption of light by a rotating sector caused the rate of the reaction to vary with the frequency of the sector and, in 1926, he was the first to apply this theory to measure the 'mean life' of a reaction intermediate.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] Deflagrations are often used in engineering applications when the force of the expanding gas is used to move an object such as a projectile down a barrel, or a piston in an internal combustion engine.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] Deflagration systems and products can also be used in mining, demolition and stone quarrying via gas pressure blasting as a beneficial alternative to high explosives.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] When studying or discussing explosive safety, or the safety of systems containing explosives, the terms deflagration, detonation and deflagration-to-detonation transition (commonly referred to as DDT) must be understood and used appropriately to convey relevant information.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] As explained above, a deflagration is a subsonic reaction, whereas a detonation is a supersonic (greater than the sound speed of the material) reaction.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] Distinguishing between a deflagration or a detonation can be difficult to impossible to the casual observer.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] Rather, confidently differentiating between the two requires instrumentation and diagnostics to ascertain reaction speed in the affected material.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] Therefore, when an unexpected event or an accident occurs with an explosive material or an explosive-containing system, it is usually impossible to know whether the explosive deflagrated or detonated as both can appear as very violent, energetic reactions.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] Therefore, the energetic materials community coined the term "high explosive violent reaction" or "HEVR" to describe a violent reaction that, because it lacked diagnostics to measure sound-speed, could have been either a deflagration or a detonation.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] The underlying flame physics can be understood with the help of an idealized model consisting of a uniform one-dimensional tube of unburnt and burned gaseous fuel, separated by a thin transitional region of width $\delta \;$ in which the burning occurs.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] The burning region is commonly referred to as the flame or flame front.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] In equilibrium, thermal diffusion across the flame front is balanced by the heat supplied by burning.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] Two characteristic timescales are important here.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] where $\kappa \;$ is the thermal diffusivity.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] where $\Delta U\;$ is the activation barrier for the burning reaction and $T_{f}\;$ is the temperature developed as the result of burning; the value of this so-called "flame temperature" can be determined from the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] For a stationary moving (unclear) deflagration front, these two timescales must be equal: the heat generated by burning is equal to the heat carried away by heat transfer.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] This simplified model neglects the change of temperature and thus the burning rate across the deflagration front.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] This model also neglects the possible influence of turbulence.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] As a result, this derivation gives only the laminar flame speed—hence the designation $S_{l}\;$ .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] Damage to buildings, equipment and people can result from a large-scale, short-duration deflagration.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] The potential damage is primarily a function of the total amount of fuel burned in the event (total energy available), the maximum reaction velocity that is achieved, and the manner in which the expansion of the combustion gases is contained.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] Vented deflagrations tend to be less violent or damaging than contained deflagrations.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] In free-air deflagrations, there is a continuous variation in deflagration effects relative to the maximum flame velocity.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] When flame velocities are low, the effect of a deflagration is to release heat, such as in a flash fire.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/deflagration] At flame velocities near the speed of sound, the energy released is in the form of pressure, and the resulting high pressure can damage equipment and buildings.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Detonations occur in both conventional solid and liquid explosives, as well as in reactive gases.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] TNT, dynamite, and C4 are examples of high power explosives that detonate.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] The velocity of detonation in solid and liquid explosives is much higher than that in gaseous ones, which allows the wave system to be observed with greater detail (higher resolution).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] A very wide variety of fuels may occur as gases (e.g. hydrogen), droplet fogs, or dust suspensions.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] In addition to dioxygen, oxidants can include halogen compounds, ozone, hydrogen peroxide, and oxides of nitrogen.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Gaseous detonations are often associated with a mixture of fuel and oxidant in a composition somewhat below conventional flammability ratios.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] They happen most often in confined systems, but they sometimes occur in large vapor clouds.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Other materials, such as acetylene, ozone, and hydrogen peroxide, are detonable in the absence of an oxidant (or reductant).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] In these cases the energy released results from the rearrangement of the molecular constituents of the material.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Detonation was discovered in 1881 by four French scientists Marcellin Berthelot and Paul Marie Eugène Vieille and Ernest-François Mallard and Henry Louis Le Chatelier.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] The mathematical predictions of propagation were carried out first by David Chapman in 1899 and by Émile Jouguet in 1905, 1906 and 1917.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] The next advance in understanding detonation was made by John von Neumann and Werner Döring in the early 1940s and Yakov B.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Zel'dovich and Aleksandr Solomonovich Kompaneets in the 1960s.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] The simplest theory to predict the behaviour of detonations in gases is known as the Chapman–Jouguet (CJ) condition, developed around the turn of the 20th century.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] This theory, described by a relatively simple set of algebraic equations, models the detonation as a propagating shock wave accompanied by exothermic heat release.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Such a theory describes the chemistry and diffusive transport processes as occurring abruptly as the shock passes.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] A more complex theory was advanced during World War II independently by Zel'dovich, von Neumann, and Döring.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] This theory, now known as ZND theory, admits finite-rate chemical reactions and thus describes a detonation as an infinitesimally thin shock wave, followed by a zone of exothermic chemical reaction.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] With a reference frame of a stationary shock, the following flow is subsonic, so that an acoustic reaction zone follows immediately behind the lead front, the Chapman–Jouguet condition.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] There is also some evidence that the reaction zone is semi-metallic in some explosives.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Both theories describe one-dimensional and steady wavefronts.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] However, in the 1960s, experiments revealed that gas-phase detonations were most often characterized by unsteady, three-dimensional structures, which can only, in an averaged sense, be predicted by one-dimensional steady theories.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] The Wood-Kirkwood detonation theory can correct some of these limitations.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Experimental studies have revealed some of the conditions needed for the propagation of such fronts.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] In confinement, the range of composition of mixes of fuel and oxidant and self-decomposing substances with inerts are slightly below the flammability limits and, for spherically expanding fronts, well below them.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] The influence of increasing the concentration of diluent on expanding individual detonation cells has been elegantly demonstrated.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Similarly, their size grows as the initial pressure falls.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Since cell widths must be matched with minimum dimension of containment, any wave overdriven by the initiator will be quenched.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Mathematical modeling has steadily advanced to predicting the complex flow fields behind shocks inducing reactions.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] To date, none has adequately described how the structure is formed and sustained behind unconfined waves.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] When used in explosive devices, the main cause of damage from a detonation is the supersonic blast front (a powerful shock wave) in the surrounding area.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] This is a significant distinction from deflagrations where the exothermic wave is subsonic and maximum pressures for non-metal specks of dust are approximately 7–10 times atmospheric pressure.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Therefore, detonation is a feature for destructive purposes while deflagration is favored for the acceleration of firearms' projectiles.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] However, detonation waves may also be used for less destructive purposes, including deposition of coatings to a surface or cleaning of equipment (e.g. slag removal) and even explosively welding together metals that would otherwise fail to fuse.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Pulse detonation engines use the detonation wave for aerospace propulsion.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] The first flight of an aircraft powered by a pulse detonation engine took place at the Mojave Air & Space Port on January 31, 2008.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Unintentional detonation when deflagration is desired is a problem in some devices.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] In Otto cycle, or gasoline engines it is called engine knocking or pinging, and it causes a loss of power.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] It can also cause excessive heating, and harsh mechanical shock that can result in eventual engine failure.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] In firearms, it may cause catastrophic and potentially lethal failure.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/detonation] Pulse detonation engines are a form of pulsed jet engine that has been experimented with on several occasions as this offers the potential for good fuel efficiency.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/flow-velocity] In continuum mechanics the **flow velocity** in fluid dynamics, also **macroscopic velocity** in statistical mechanics, or **drift velocity** in electromagnetism, is a vector field used to mathematically describe the motion of a continuum.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/flow-velocity] The length of the flow velocity vector is scalar, the ***flow speed***.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/flow-velocity] It is also called **velocity field**; when evaluated along a line, it is called a **velocity profile** (as in, e.g., law of the wall).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/flow-velocity] The flow velocity of a fluid effectively describes everything about the motion of a fluid.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/flow-velocity] Many physical properties of a fluid can be expressed mathematically in terms of the flow velocity.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/flow-velocity] The flow of a fluid is said to be *steady* if $\mathbf {u}$ does not vary with time.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/flow-velocity] That is, if $\mathbf {u}$ is a solenoidal vector field.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/flow-velocity] That is, if $\mathbf {u}$ is an irrotational vector field.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/flow-velocity] If the vorticity is zero, the flow is irrotational.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/flow-velocity] The scalar field $\phi$ is called the velocity potential for the flow.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] In vector calculus, the **gradient** of a scalar-valued differentiable function f of several variables is the vector field (or vector-valued function) $\nabla f$ whose value at a point p gives the direction and the rate of fastest increase.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient transforms like a vector under change of basis of the space of variables of f .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] If the gradient of a function is non-zero at a point p , the direction of the gradient is the direction in which the function increases most quickly from p , and the magnitude of the gradient is the rate of increase in that direction, the greatest absolute directional derivative.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Further, a point where the gradient is the zero vector is known as a stationary point.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient thus plays a fundamental role in optimization theory, machine learning, and artificial intelligence, where it is used to minimize a function by gradient descent.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] where $df$ is the total infinitesimal change in f for an infinitesimal displacement $d\mathbf {r}$ , and is seen to be maximal when $d\mathbf {r}$ is in the direction of the gradient $\nabla f$ .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The nabla symbol $\nabla$ , written as an upside-down triangle and pronounced "del", denotes the vector differential operator.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] When a coordinate system is used in which the basis vectors are not functions of position, the gradient is given by the vector whose components are the partial derivatives of f at p .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Note that the above definition for gradient is defined for the function f only if f is differentiable at p .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] There can be functions for which partial derivatives exist in every direction but fail to be differentiable.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Furthermore, this definition as the vector of partial derivatives is only valid when the basis of the coordinate system is orthonormal.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] For any other basis, the metric tensor at that point needs to be taken into account.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] For example, the function $f(x,y)={\frac {x^{2}y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}}$ unless at origin where $f(0,0)=0$ , is not differentiable at the origin as it does not have a well defined tangent plane despite having well defined partial derivatives in every direction at the origin.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] In this particular example, under rotation of x-y coordinate system, the above formula for gradient fails to transform like a vector (gradient becomes dependent on choice of basis for coordinate system) and also fails to point towards the 'steepest ascent' in some orientations.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] For differentiable functions where the formula for gradient holds, it can be shown to always transform as a vector under transformation of the basis so as to always point towards the fastest increase.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient is dual to the total derivative $df$ : the value of the gradient at a point is a tangent vector – a vector at each point; while the value of the derivative at a point is a *co*tangent vector – a linear functional on vectors.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient admits multiple generalizations to more general functions on manifolds; see § Generalizations.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Consider a room where the temperature is given by a scalar field, *T*, so at each point (*x*, *y*, *z*) the temperature is *T*(*x*, *y*, *z*), independent of time.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] At each point in the room, the gradient of *T* at that point will show the direction in which the temperature rises most quickly, moving away from (*x*, *y*, *z*).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The magnitude of the gradient will determine how fast the temperature rises in that direction.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Consider a surface whose height above sea level at point (*x*, *y*) is *H*(*x*, *y*).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient of *H* at a point is a plane vector pointing in the direction of the steepest slope or grade at that point.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The steepness of the slope at that point is given by the magnitude of the gradient vector.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient can also be used to measure how a scalar field changes in other directions, rather than just the direction of greatest change, by taking a dot product.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Suppose that the steepest slope on a hill is 40%.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] A road going directly uphill has slope 40%, but a road going around the hill at an angle will have a shallower slope.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] More generally, if the hill height function *H* is differentiable, then the gradient of *H* dotted with a unit vector gives the slope of the hill in the direction of the vector, the directional derivative of *H* along the unit vector.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient of a function f at point a is usually written as $\nabla f(a)$ .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient (or gradient vector field) of a scalar function *f*(*x*1, *x*2, *x*3, …, *xn*) is denoted ∇*f* or ∇→*f* where ∇ (nabla) denotes the vector differential operator, del.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The notation grad *f* is also commonly used to represent the gradient.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient of *f* is defined as the unique vector field whose dot product with any vector **v** at each point *x* is the directional derivative of *f* along **v**.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] where the right-hand side is the directional derivative and there are many ways to represent it.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Formally, the derivative is *dual* to the gradient; see relationship with derivative.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] When a function also depends on a parameter such as time, the gradient often refers simply to the vector of its spatial derivatives only (see Spatial gradient).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The magnitude and direction of the gradient vector are independent of the particular coordinate representation.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] where **i**, **j**, **k** are the standard unit vectors in the directions of the *x*, *y* and *z* coordinates, respectively.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] In some applications it is customary to represent the gradient as a row vector or column vector of its components in a rectangular coordinate system; this article follows the convention of the gradient being a column vector, while the derivative is a row vector.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] where *ρ* is the axial distance, *φ* is the azimuthal or azimuth angle, *z* is the axial coordinate, and **e***ρ*, **e***φ* and **e***z* are unit vectors pointing along the coordinate directions.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] where *r* is the radial distance, *φ* is the azimuthal angle and *θ* is the polar angle, and **e***r*, **e***θ* and **e***φ* are again local unit vectors pointing in the coordinate directions (that is, the normalized covariant basis).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] For the gradient in other orthogonal coordinate systems, see Orthogonal coordinates (Differential operators in three dimensions).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] We consider general coordinates, which we write as *x*1, …, *x**i*, …, *x**n*, where n is the number of dimensions of the domain.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Here, the upper index refers to the position in the list of the coordinate or component, so *x*2 refers to the second component—not the quantity *x* squared.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The index variable *i* refers to an arbitrary element *x**i*.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] where $\mathbf {e} ^{i}=\mathrm {d} x^{i}$ and $\mathbf {e} _{i}=\partial \mathbf {x} /\partial x^{i}$ refer to the unnormalized local covariant and contravariant bases respectively, $g^{ij}$ is the inverse metric tensor, and the Einstein summation convention implies summation over *i* and *j*.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] where we cannot use Einstein notation, since it is impossible to avoid the repetition of more than two indices.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Despite the use of upper and lower indices, $\mathbf {\hat {e}} _{i}$ , $\mathbf {\hat {e}} ^{i}$ , and $h_{i}$ are neither contravariant nor covariant.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The latter expression evaluates to the expressions given above for cylindrical and spherical coordinates.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient is closely related to the total derivative (total differential) $df$ : they are transpose (dual) to each other.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] In symbols, the gradient is an element of the tangent space at a point, $\nabla f(p)\in T_{p}\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , while the derivative is a map from the tangent space to the real numbers, $df_{p}\colon T_{p}\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The best linear approximation to a differentiable function $f:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ at a point x in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is a linear map from $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ to $\mathbb {R}$ which is often denoted by $df_{x}$ or $Df(x)$ and called the differential or total derivative of f at x .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The function $df$ , which maps x to $df_{x}$ , is called the total differential or exterior derivative of f and is an example of a differential 1-form.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Much as the derivative of a function of a single variable represents the slope of the tangent to the graph of the function, the directional derivative of a function in several variables represents the slope of the tangent hyperplane in the direction of the vector.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient is related to the differential by the formula $(\nabla f)_{x}\cdot v=df_{x}(v)$ for any $v\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , where $\cdot$ is the dot product: taking the dot product of a vector with the gradient is the same as taking the directional derivative along the vector.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The best linear approximation to a function can be expressed in terms of the gradient, rather than the derivative.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient of a function f from the Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ to $\mathbb {R}$ at any particular point $x_{0}$ in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ characterizes the best linear approximation to f at $x_{0}$ .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] for x close to $x_{0}$ , where $(\nabla f)_{x_{0}}$ is the gradient of f computed at $x_{0}$ , and the dot denotes the dot product on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] This equation is equivalent to the first two terms in the multivariable Taylor series expansion of f at $x_{0}$ .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] If the function *f* : *U* → **R** is differentiable, then the differential of *f* is the Fréchet derivative of *f*.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] There are two forms of the chain rule applying to the gradient.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] More generally, if instead *I* ⊂ **R***k*, then the following holds: $\nabla (f\circ g)(c)={\big (}Dg(c){\big )}^{\mathsf {T}}{\big (}\nabla f(a){\big )},$ where (*Dg*)T denotes the transpose Jacobian matrix.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] For the second form of the chain rule, suppose that *h* : *I* → **R** is a real valued function on a subset *I* of **R**, and that *h* is differentiable at the point *f*(*a*) ∈ *I*.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] A level surface, or isosurface, is the set of all points where some function has a given value.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] If *f* is differentiable, then the dot product (∇*f* )*x* ⋅ *v* of the gradient at a point *x* with a vector *v* gives the directional derivative of *f* at *x* in the direction *v*.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] It follows that in this case the gradient of *f* is orthogonal to the level sets of *f*.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] For example, a level surface in three-dimensional space is defined by an equation of the form *F*(*x*, *y*, *z*) = *c*.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient of *F* is then normal to the surface.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] More generally, any embedded hypersurface in a Riemannian manifold can be cut out by an equation of the form *F*(*P*) = 0 such that *dF* is nowhere zero.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient of *F* is then normal to the hypersurface.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Similarly, an affine algebraic hypersurface may be defined by an equation *F*(*x*1, ..., *x**n*) = 0, where *F* is a polynomial.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient of *F* is zero at a singular point of the hypersurface (this is the definition of a singular point).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] At a non-singular point, it is a nonzero normal vector.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The gradient of a function is called a gradient field.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] A (continuous) gradient field is always a conservative vector field: its line integral along any path depends only on the endpoints of the path, and can be evaluated by the gradient theorem (the fundamental theorem of calculus for line integrals).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Conversely, a (continuous) conservative vector field is always the gradient of a function.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Let $v\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ be an arbitrary unit vector.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] where R denotes higher order terms in $vh$ .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The Jacobian matrix is the generalization of the gradient for vector-valued functions of several variables and differentiable maps between Euclidean spaces or, more generally, manifolds.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] A further generalization for a function between Banach spaces is the Fréchet derivative.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Suppose **f** : **R***n* → **R***m* is a function such that each of its first-order partial derivatives exist on ℝ*n*.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Then the Jacobian matrix of **f** is defined to be an *m*×*n* matrix, denoted by $\mathbf {J} _{\mathbb {f} }(\mathbb {x} )$ or simply $\mathbf {J}$ .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] Since the total derivative of a vector field is a linear mapping from vectors to vectors, it is a tensor quantity.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] (where the Einstein summation notation is used and the tensor product of the vectors **e***i* and **e***k* is a dyadic tensor of type (2,0)).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] where *g**jk* are the components of the inverse metric tensor and the **e***i* are the coordinate basis vectors.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/gradient] The relation between the exterior derivative and the gradient of a function on **R***n* is a special case of this in which the metric is the flat metric given by the dot product.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] An **explosive** is a reactive substance that contains a great amount of potential energy that can produce an explosion if released suddenly, usually accompanied by the production of light, heat, sound, and pressure.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] An explosive charge is a measured quantity of explosive material.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The material may either be composed solely of one ingredient or be a mixture containing at least two substances.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] An explosive can be used together with mechanical or electronic components to manufacture a bomb.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The potential energy can be stored in an explosive material in various ways.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Most commonly it is stored as chemical energy, such as black powder, nitroglycerin or even grain dust.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] It can also be stored as pressurized gas, like a gas cylinder, aerosol can, or boiling liquid expanding vapor explosion, or less commonly as nuclear energy, such as in the fissile isotopes uranium-235 and plutonium-239.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Explosive materials may be categorized by the speed at which they expand.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Explosives may also be categorized by their sensitivity.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Sensitive materials that can be initiated by a relatively small amount of heat or pressure are primary explosives, and materials that are relatively insensitive are secondary or tertiary explosives.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Such materials require a detonator to initiate the explosion, without which they will deflagrate instead.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Only some of the manufactured chemicals are suitable to be used as explosives.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The remainders are too dangerous, sensitive, toxic, expensive, unstable, or prone to decomposition or degradation over short time spans.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] In contrast, some materials are merely combustible or flammable if they burn without exploding.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The distinction, however, is not always clear.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Certain materials—dusts, powders, gases, or volatile organic liquids—may simply be combustible or flammable under ordinary conditions but become explosive in specific situations or forms, such as dispersed airborne clouds, confinement, or sudden release.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Early thermal weapons, such as Greek fire, have existed since ancient times.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The history of chemical explosives is closely intertwined with the history of gunpowder.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] While searching for an elixir of eternal life, Taoist alchemists in China created the earliest form of gunpowder from coal, saltpeter, and sulfur.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Gunpowder was the first form of chemical explosives, first seeing use in warfare in 1161.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Early forms of explosives in warfare included bamboo firecrackers, which were explosives fired from bamboo or bronze tubes.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The first explosive stronger than black powder to see widespread use was nitroglycerin, developed in 1847.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Since nitroglycerin is a liquid and highly unstable, it was replaced by nitrocellulose and trinitrotoluene (TNT) in 1863, smokeless powder and dynamite in 1867, and gelignite.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] World War I saw the adoption of TNT in artillery shells, while World War II saw extensive use of new explosives .
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] In modern weapons, these have largely been replaced by more powerful explosives such as C-4 and pentaerythritol tetranitrate (PETN), which are waterproof and malleable, though they may catch fire due to reactions with metals.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] An **explosive device** typically refers to a bomb that is not used by a military.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] It contains an explosive with a detonator connected to a triggering mechanism to form a device used for a specific purpose.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The largest commercial application of explosives is mining.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The detonation or deflagration of either a high or low explosive in a confined space can be used to liberate a fairly specific sub-volume of a brittle material (rock) in a much larger volume of the same or similar material.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The mining industry tends to use nitrate-based explosives such as emulsions of fuel oil and ammonium nitrate solutions, mixtures of ammonium nitrate prills (fertilizer pellets), fuel oil (ANFO), and gelatinous suspensions or slurries of ammonium nitrate and combustible fuels.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] In materials science and engineering, explosives are used in cladding (explosion welding).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] This is a solid state (solid-phase) process where welding is accomplished by accelerating one of the components at extremely high velocity through the use of explosives.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] This process is often used to clad carbon steel or aluminium plate with a thin layer of a harder or more corrosion-resistant material.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] An explosion is a type of spontaneous chemical reaction that, once initiated, is driven by both a large exothermic change and a large positive entropy change in going from reactants to products, thereby constituting a thermodynamically favorable process that propagates very rapidly.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Thus, explosives are substances that contain a large amount of energy stored in chemical bonds.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The energetic stability of the gaseous products, and hence their generation, comes from the formation of strongly bonded species like carbon monoxide, carbon dioxide, and nitrogen gas, which contain strong double and triple bonds having bond strengths of nearly 1 MJ/mole.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Consequently, most commercial explosives are organic compounds containing –NO2, –ONO2, and –NHNO2 groups that, when detonated, release gases like the aforementioned (e.g., nitroglycerin, TNT, octogen (HMX), PETN, nitrocellulose).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Traditional explosives mechanics are based on the shock-sensitive rapid oxidation of carbon and hydrogen to carbon dioxide, carbon monoxide, and water in the form of steam.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Nitrates typically provide the required oxygen to burn the carbon and hydrogen fuel.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] A sensitizer such as powdered aluminum may be added to an explosive to increase the energy of the detonation.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Once detonated, the nitrogen portion of the explosive formulation emerges as nitrogen gas and toxic nitric oxides.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The chemical decomposition of an explosive may take years, days, hours, or a fraction of a second.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The slower processes of decomposition take place in storage and are of interest only from a stability standpoint.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Of more interest are the other two rapid forms besides decomposition: deflagration and detonation.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] In addition to chemical and nuclear explosives, there are more exotic explosive materials.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] An explosive is classified as a low or high explosive according to its rate of combustion: low explosives deflagrate (burn rapidly), while high explosives detonate.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] While these definitions are distinct, the problem of precisely measuring rapid decomposition makes practical classification of explosives difficult.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] For a reaction to be classified as a detonation as opposed to just a deflagration, the propagation of the reaction shockwave through the material being tested must be faster than the speed of sound through that material.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The speed of sound through a liquid or solid material is usually orders of magnitude faster than the speed of sound through air or other gases.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Low explosives (or low-order explosives) are explosive materials that deflagrate, meaning that the explosion is propagated by a flame front that proceeds through the material at a subsonic speed.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Under normal conditions, low explosives undergo deflagration at rates that vary from a few centimetres per second to approximately 0.4 kilometres per second (Mach 1.2; 1,300 ft/s).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] It is possible for them to deflagrate more quickly, producing an effect similar to a detonation.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] This can happen under higher pressure (such as when gunpowder deflagrates inside the confined space of a bullet casing, accelerating the bullet to well beyond the speed of sound) or temperature.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] A low explosive is usually a mixture of a combustible substance and an oxidant that decomposes rapidly; however, they burn more slowly than a high explosive, which has an extremely fast burn rate.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Low explosives are normally employed as propellants.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Included in this group are petroleum products such as propane and gasoline, gunpowder (including smokeless powder), and light pyrotechnics such as flares and fireworks, but they can replace high explosives in certain applications, including gas pressure blasting.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] High explosives (HE, or high-order explosives) are explosive materials that detonate, meaning that the explosion is propagated by an explosive shock front that passes through the material at supersonic speed.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] High explosives detonate with an explosive velocity of about 3–9 kilometres per second (9,800–29,500 ft/s).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] For instance, TNT has a detonation (burn) rate of approximately 6.9 km/s (Mach 20; 4.3 mi/s), detonating cord of 6.7 km/s (Mach 20; 4.2 mi/s), and C-4 about 8.0 km/s (Mach 24; 5.0 mi/s).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] High explosives tend to have the fuel and oxidizer contained in the same molecule (e.g.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] TNT) while low explosives like gunpowder are usually mixtures of fuel (e.g. the sulfur and charcoal in gunpowder) and oxidizer (the saltpeter in gunpowder), causing the reaction front to propagate subsonically (deflagration).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] High explosives are normally employed in mining, demolition, and military applications.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] High explosives can be divided into two explosive classes differentiated by sensitivity: primary explosives and secondary explosives.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Although tertiary explosives (such as ANFO at 3.2 km/s (Mach 9.4; 2.0 mi/s) can technically meet the explosive velocity definition, they are not considered high explosives in regulatory contexts.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Countless high-explosive compounds are chemically possible, but commercially and militarily important ones have included NG, TNT, TNP, IMX-101, RDX, HMX, PETN, EGDN, TATB, and HNS.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] A **primary explosive** is an explosive that is extremely sensitive to stimuli such as impact, friction, heat, static electricity, or electromagnetic radiation.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Some primary explosives are also known as contact explosives.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] A relatively small amount of energy is required for initiation.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] As a very general rule, primary explosives are considered to be those compounds that are more sensitive than PETN.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] As a practical measure, primary explosives are sufficiently sensitive that they can be reliably initiated with a blow from a hammer; however, PETN can also usually be initiated in this manner, so this is only a very broad guideline.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Additionally, several compounds, such as nitrogen triiodide, are so sensitive that they cannot even be handled without detonating.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Nitrogen triiodide is so sensitive that it can be reliably detonated by exposure to alpha radiation.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Primary explosives are often used in detonators or to trigger larger charges of less sensitive secondary explosives.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Primary explosives are commonly used in blasting caps and percussion caps to translate a physical shock signal.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] In other situations, different signals, such as electrical or physical shock, or, in the case of laser detonation systems, light, are used to initiate an action, i.e., an explosion.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] A small quantity, typically milligrams, is sufficient to initiate a larger charge of explosive that is usually safer to handle.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] A **secondary explosive** is less sensitive than a primary explosive and requires substantially more energy to be initiated.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Because they are less sensitive, they are usable in a wider variety of applications and are safer to handle and store.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Secondary explosives are used in larger quantities in an explosive train and are usually initiated by a smaller quantity of a primary explosive.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Examples of secondary explosives include TNT and hexogen (RDX).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Most tertiaries include a fuel and an oxidizer.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] ANFO can be a tertiary explosive if its reaction rate is slow.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Explosives are often characterized by the physical form that the explosives are produced or used in.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Shipping labels and tags may include both United Nations and national markings.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] United Nations markings include numbered Hazard Class and Division (HC/D) codes and alphabetic Compatibility Group codes.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Though the two are related, they are separate and distinct.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Any Compatibility Group designator can be assigned to any Hazard Class and Division.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] An example of this hybrid marking would be a consumer firework, which is labeled as 1.4G or 1.4S.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Examples of national markings would include United States Department of Transportation (U.S.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The UN GHS Hazard Class and Division (HC/D) is a numeric designator within a hazard class indicating the character, predominance of associated hazards, and potential for causing personnel casualties and property damage.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] It is an internationally accepted system that communicates, using the minimum amount of markings, the primary hazard associated with a substance.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] To see an entire UNO table, browse Paragraphs 3–8 and 3–9 of NAVSEA OP 5, Vol.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Compatibility Group codes are used to indicate storage compatibility for HC/D Class 1 (explosive) materials.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Letters are used to designate 13 compatibility groups as follows.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] To determine the suitability of an explosive substance for a particular use, its physical properties must first be known.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The usefulness of an explosive can only be appreciated when the properties and the factors affecting them are fully understood.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Sensitivity refers to the ease with which an explosive can be ignited or detonated, i.e., the amount and intensity of shock, friction, or heat that is required.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] When the term sensitivity is used, care must be taken to clarify what kind of sensitivity is under discussion.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The relative sensitivity of a given explosive to impact may vary greatly from its sensitivity to friction or heat.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] These factors present special hazards that may rule out any practical utility.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Sensitivity is an important consideration in selecting an explosive for a particular purpose.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The explosive in an armor-piercing projectile must be relatively insensitive, or the shock of impact would cause it to detonate before it penetrated to the point desired.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The explosive lenses around nuclear charges are also designed to be highly insensitive to minimize the risk of accidental detonation.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The index of the capacity of an explosive to be initiated into detonation in a sustained manner.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] It is defined by the power of the detonator, which is certain to prime the explosive to a sustained and continuous detonation.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Reference is made to the Sellier-Bellot scale that consists of a series of 10 detonators, from n.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] 10, each of which corresponds to an increasing charge weight.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] In practice, most of the explosives on the market today are sensitive to an n.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] 8 detonator, where the charge corresponds to 2 grams of mercury fulminate.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The velocity with which the reaction process propagates in the mass of the explosive.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Most commercial mining explosives have detonation velocities ranging from 1,800 m/s to 8,000 m/s.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Today, the velocity of detonation can be measured with accuracy.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Together with density, it is an important element influencing the yield of the energy transmitted through both atmospheric overpressure and ground acceleration.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] By definition, a "low explosive", such as black powder or smokeless gunpowder, has a burn rate of 171–631 m/s.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] In contrast, a "high explosive", whether a primary, such as detonating cord, or a secondary, such as TNT or C-4, has a significantly higher burn rate of about 6900–8092 m/s.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The term *power* or *performance* as applied to an explosive, refers to its ability to do work.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] In practice it is defined as the explosive's ability to accomplish what is intended in the way of energy delivery (i.e., fragment projection, air blast, high-velocity jet, underwater shock and bubble energy, etc.).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Explosive power or performance is evaluated by a tailored series of tests to assess the material for its intended use.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Of the tests listed below, cylinder expansion and air-blast tests are common to most testing programs, and the others support specific applications.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] In addition to strength, explosives display a second characteristic, which is their shattering effect, or brisance (from the French meaning "to break").
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Brisance is important in determining the effectiveness of an explosion in fragmenting shells, bomb casings, and grenades.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The rapidity with which an explosive reaches its peak pressure (power) is a measure of its brisance.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Brisance values are primarily employed in France and Russia.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The sand crush test is commonly employed to determine the relative brisance in comparison to TNT.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] No test is capable of directly comparing the explosive properties of two or more compounds; it is important to examine the data from several such tests (sand crush, trauzl, and so forth) in order to gauge relative brisance.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] True values for comparison require field experiments.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Density of loading refers to the mass of an explosive per unit volume.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Several methods of loading are available, including pellet loading, cast loading, and press loading, the choice being determined by the characteristics of the explosive.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Dependent upon the method employed, an average density of the loaded charge can be obtained that is within 80–99% of the theoretical maximum density of the explosive.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] High load density can reduce sensitivity by making the mass more resistant to internal friction.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] However, if density is increased to the extent that individual crystals are crushed, the explosive may become more sensitive.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Increased load density also permits the use of more explosives, thereby increasing the power of the warhead.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] It is possible to compress an explosive beyond a point of sensitivity, known also as *dead-pressing*, in which the material is no longer capable of being reliably initiated, if at all.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Volatility is the readiness with which a substance vaporizes.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Excessive volatility often results in the development of pressure within rounds of ammunition and separation of mixtures into their constituents.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Volatility affects the chemical composition of the explosive such that a marked reduction in stability may occur, which results in an increase in the danger of handling.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The introduction of water into an explosive is highly undesirable since it reduces the sensitivity, strength, and velocity of detonation of the explosive.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Hygroscopicity is a measure of a material's moisture-absorbing tendencies.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Moisture affects explosives adversely by acting as an inert material that absorbs heat when vaporized and by acting as a solvent medium that can cause undesired chemical reactions.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Sensitivity, strength, and velocity of detonation are reduced by inert materials that reduce the continuity of the explosive mass.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] When the moisture content evaporates during detonation, cooling occurs, which reduces the temperature of the reaction.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Stability is also affected by the presence of moisture since moisture promotes decomposition of the explosive and, in addition, causes corrosion of the explosive's metal container.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Explosives considerably differ from one another as to their behavior in the presence of water.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Gelatin dynamites containing nitroglycerin have a degree of water resistance.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Explosives based on ammonium nitrate have little or no water resistance as ammonium nitrate is highly soluble in water and is hygroscopic.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Many explosives are toxic to some extent.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Manufacturing inputs can also be organic compounds or hazardous materials that require special handling due to risks (such as carcinogens).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The decomposition products, residual solids, or gases of some explosives can be toxic, whereas others are harmless, such as carbon dioxide and water.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] "Green explosives" seek to reduce environmental and health impacts.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] An example of such is the lead-free primary explosive copper(I) 5-nitrotetrazolate, an alternative to lead azide.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Explosive material may be incorporated in the explosive train of a device or system.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] An example is a pyrotechnic lead igniting a booster, which causes the main charge to detonate.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The most widely used explosives are condensed liquids or solids converted to gaseous products by explosive chemical reactions and the energy released by those reactions.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The gaseous products of complete reaction are typically carbon dioxide, steam, and nitrogen.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Gaseous volumes computed by the ideal gas law tend to be too large at high pressures characteristic of explosions.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Ultimate volume expansion may be estimated at three orders of magnitude, or one liter per gram of explosive.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Explosives with an oxygen deficit will generate soot or gases like carbon monoxide and hydrogen, which may react with surrounding materials such as atmospheric oxygen.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Attempts to obtain more precise volume estimates must consider the possibility of such side reactions, condensation of steam, and aqueous solubility of gases like carbon dioxide.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Oxygen balance is an expression that is used to indicate the degree to which an explosive can be oxidized.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] If an explosive molecule contains enough oxygen to convert all of its carbon to carbon dioxide, all of its hydrogen to water, and all of its metal to metal oxide with no excess, the molecule has a zero oxygen balance.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The molecule has a positive oxygen balance if it contains more oxygen than is needed and a negative oxygen balance if it contains less oxygen than is needed.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The sensitivity, strength, and brisance of an explosive are all somewhat dependent upon oxygen balance and tend to approach their maxima as oxygen balance approaches zero.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] A chemical explosive may consist of either a chemically pure compound, such as nitroglycerin, or a mixture of a fuel and an oxidizer, such as black powder or grain dust and air.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Some chemical compounds are unstable in that, when shocked, they react, possibly to the point of detonation.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Each molecule of the compound dissociates into two or more new molecules (generally gases) with the release of energy.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The above compositions may describe most of the explosive material, but a practical explosive will often include small percentages of other substances.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] For example, dynamite is a mixture of highly sensitive nitroglycerin with sawdust, powdered silica, or, most commonly, diatomaceous earth, which act as stabilizers.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Plastics and polymers may be added to bind powders of explosive compounds; waxes may be incorporated to make them safer to handle; aluminium powder may be introduced to increase total energy and blast effects.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Explosive compounds are also often "alloyed": HMX or RDX powders may be mixed (typically by melt-casting) with TNT to form Octol or Cyclotol.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] An oxidizer is a pure substance (molecule) that in a chemical reaction can contribute some atoms of one or more oxidizing elements, in which the fuel component of the explosive burns.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] On the simplest level, the oxidizer may itself be an oxidizing element, such as gaseous or liquid oxygen.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] There are more exotic methods of causing explosions.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Examples include abruptly heating a substance to a plasma state with a high-intensity laser or electric arc.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Laser- and arc-heating are used in laser detonators, exploding-bridgewire detonators, and exploding foil initiators, where a shock wave and then detonation in conventional chemical explosive material is created by laser or electric arc heating.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Laser and electric energy are not currently used in practice to generate most of the required energy but only to initiate reactions.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The legality of possessing or using explosives varies by jurisdiction.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] Various countries around the world have enacted explosives laws and require licenses to manufacture, distribute, store, use, or possess explosives or ingredients.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] In the Netherlands, the civil and commercial use of explosives is covered under the *Wet explosieven voor civiel gebruik* (explosives for civil use Act), in accordance with EU directive nr.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The illegal use of explosives is covered under the *Wet Wapens en Munitie* (Weapons and Munition Act) (Dutch).
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] During World War I, numerous laws were created to regulate war-related industries and increase security within the United States.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] In 1917, the 65th United States Congress created many laws, including the *Espionage Act of 1917* and the *Explosives Act of 1917*.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The *Explosives Act of 1917* (session 1, chapter 83, 40 Stat.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] 385) was signed on 6 October 1917 and went into effect on 16 November 1917.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The legal summary is "An Act to prohibit the manufacture, distribution, storage, use, and possession in *time of war* of explosives, providing regulations for the safe manufacture, distribution, storage, use, and possession of the same, and for other purposes".
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] This was the first federal regulation of licensing explosives purchases.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The act was deactivated after World War I ended.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] After the United States entered World War II, the Explosives Act of 1917 was reactivated.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] In 1947, the act was deactivated by President Truman.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] The *Organized Crime Control Act of 1970* (Pub.
[src:chapman-jouguet-condition/high-explosive] 91–452) transferred many explosives regulations to the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms (ATF) of the Department of Treasury.
